Implement a fluent builder API for runtime configuration, providing discoverability and validation at construction time rather than runtime.

## Strategic Value

**Problem Solved**: Runtime configuration is scattered across multiple types (LabConfig, RuntimeConfig, etc.). Users must know which options exist and how they interact. Builder pattern centralizes this.

**Why Builder Pattern**: 
- Fluent API is discoverable via IDE autocomplete
- Validation happens at build() time, not later
- Optional features have sensible defaults
- Complex configurations are still readable

**Developer Experience**: New users can configure a runtime without reading documentation by following autocomplete suggestions. This significantly lowers the barrier to entry.

## Design

### Builder Types
```rust
// Main entry point
pub struct RuntimeBuilder { /* ... */ }

// Specialized builders for subsystems
pub struct SchedulerBuilder { /* ... */ }
pub struct TimerBuilder { /* ... */ }
pub struct IoBuilder { /* ... */ }
pub struct TracingBuilder { /* ... */ }
```

### Fluent API
```rust
let runtime = RuntimeBuilder::new()
    .scheduler(|s| s
        .worker_threads(4)
        .task_queue_depth(1024)
        .scheduling_policy(Policy::WorkStealing))
    .timers(|t| t
        .resolution(Duration::from_millis(1))
        .max_duration(Duration::from_hours(24)))
    .io(|io| io
        .max_registered_sources(10_000)
        .enable_uring(true))
    .tracing(|tr| tr
        .enable_structured_logs()
        .span_events(true))
    .build()?;
```

